    "summary": "The Social War (91–87 BC) was an armed rebellion by Rome's Italian allies (socii) who demanded full Roman citizenship and the political rights that went with it. The rebels, including many peoples who had fought alongside Rome for generations, formed an alternative Italian confederacy with its own senate and capital (initially called Italica). The conflict was one of the most serious threats Rome faced during the Republic.\n\nThe war's underlying cause was the failure of the [[event:1068|Gracchi Brothers Reforms]] and subsequent proposals to extend citizenship to Italian allies, who bore military burdens equal to Roman citizens but enjoyed none of the political benefits — including the ability to vote and access to land distributions. The immediate trigger was the murder of the reform tribune Marcus Livius Drusus in 91 BC. Fighting was intense and casualties on both sides heavy; the rebels won several significant engagements.\n\nRome ultimately prevailed through military force but also by offering citizenship to most Italian communities — giving the rebels what they had fought for even as the military campaign continued. The Lex Julia of 90 BC and subsequent legislation extended Roman citizenship to virtually all free Italians, fundamentally transforming the Roman citizen body from a city-state citizenry into something approaching a national one. The war's political resolution was more important than its military outcome, as it united Italy under Roman citizenship in a way that strengthened the empire Rome was in the process of building.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_War_(91%E2%80%9387_BC)",
